🎄 Christmas is around the corner - and you definitely need to know more about Boston pianos! 😊

Learn more about the unique features of a Boston grand with @anniquegoettler and Steinway technician Thomas.
Today: the case design (based on New York‘s Steinways) with the expanded soundboard area (Steinway design from 1924!) for a rich base. 

#Bostonpianos #MadeToCreate #BostonpianosUSPs #BostonbySteinway #BostonAmbassador

#throwback to a great evening playing all Chopin Etudes in my Recitalexam 🤩 looking forward to play my very last exam on January 5th 2023🥳 on the program: Friedrich Kalkbrenner Piano Concerto No.1 in d Minor together with the Badische Philharmonie Pforzheim! 
This piano concerto - and also the composer- are nowadays nearly forgotten and not played anymore. However, what most people don’t know is that Kalkbrenner was one of the biggest and most successful composer and pianists of his time. He was the idol of Chopin, Liszt, Mendelssohn and many other big composers of the romantic era - and you can really hear his influence on their work! 
It’s such an honor and pleasure to have the opportunity to play this forgotten concerto soon - the concert is opened to the public, tickets in my bio!❤️😊

Get to know Boston 🎹! Learn more about unique features, part 2. 

Thomas, a Steinway piano technician working mainly at the @elbphilharmonie in Hamburg, met @anniquegoettler, our Boston Ambassador, to talk about the action of a Boston grand and the resulting good repetition. The action is based on @steinwayandsons‘ geometry and patent. And the hammer stems are the similar to Steinway‘s hammers, using the Steinway patent from 1868!

Having a great time here in #taiwan ❤️ as many people asked: yes, I am half taiwanese and yes, I speak Chinese 😊 I am currently visiting my relatives here and spending lots of time with my grandparents as I couldn’t come and see them for many many years 🙈 when I was young I went to Taiwan every summer during the holidays, however, after I started studying music in 2013 I didn’t have time and opportunity anymore to go back to Taiwan… I was planning to go after my Masters degree in 2020 - but then COVID hit the world 😵‍💫😖 now finally after my PhD/Konzertexamen I didn’t want to wait any longer and just had to jump on the next plane 😜 who of you is also living in two different cultures? Where do your parents come from? Was it difficult for you to be raised in two different cultures and languages? Tell me in the comments!❤️

Old pianos just hit different 😜😊 since yesterday I don’t have the keyboard in my Boston Grandpiano as there are some issues with the keys - but as I still have to practice I switched on my very old grand piano right next to it 😅🤪 sounds strange but even if I didn’t play on it anymore since I got the Boston 2 years ago I insisted on having it right next to me. Obviously you can hear that this piano had to suffer a lot under my practice routine, but also I feel deeply connected to it as I was practicing on it since I was 10 years old. Playing on it now again after this 2 years break feels like having a long talk with a very old friend about everything that happened in all this time - and also making jokes about the old times. 
However, it’s fun to play on it and everything but for the professional and detailed work I can feel that he just can’t keep up anymore out of different reasons and I am looking forward to have my Boston back 😜 how long have you been playing on your instrument? Let me know in the comments!❤️😊

Tickets and info in my bio and on my website ❤️
 
little fun fact - this is not the “original” Gewandhaus, it’s actually already the 3rd version of it in Leipzig. The very first one was built in 1781 and none other than Felix Mendelssohn Bartholdy was working as Kapellmeister there! But not only Mendelssohn was living in Leipzig. The godfather of piano literature Johann Sebastian Bach himself was living and working in Leipzig and died there in 1750. So for everyone who wants to go on a little music history trip - Leipzig is definitely one of the hotspots and should be on the top of your checklist 😜 have you ever been in Leipzig? What are the other music history hotspots that you would put on the checklist? Let me know in the comments!❤️🥳

Little piano secret: we don’t play piano with our fingers - but the full body ❤️ never forget to use your arm which will help you recreate the movements of the music! Instead of controlling each and every finger for every single note - try to keep your fingers relaxed and control the movements with your arm 😊 immediately you will feel much more relaxed while playing - but also your sound will change drastically 😇 give it a try and let me know in the comments if it helped you!❤️
